# 4. 🔁 UPDATE LIMITATIONS (§5.4)

### 📍 Section 5.4 (NPH discussion)

---

## Replace key paragraph with:

```text
The NPH exponent model captures one specific class of non-proportional hazards: frailty-dependent amplification of external hazards. It does not represent a general solution to all time-varying hazard structures.

Identification of α depends on cross-cohort variation in depletion geometry. When cohorts are similar in θ or cumulative hazard, α is weakly identified and may collapse toward 1. In such cases, the NPH adjustment should be interpreted as inactive.

The model assumes that excess hazard can be separated from baseline hazard and that amplification depends on frailty through a power-law relationship. Deviations from this structure (e.g., additive shocks, time-varying frailty, or behavioral effects) are not captured and may lead to residual bias.

As with θ0 estimation, failure modes are expected to manifest diagnostically through instability, estimator disagreement, or poor alignment of excess hazard across cohorts.
```

